ry stumbled through massive demobilization. The government struggled to hang on to power. And a new Canadian nationalism was forged. This book offers a fresh perspective on the concerns of the time: the treatment of veterans, including nurses and Indigenous soldiers; the place of children; the influenza pandemic; the rising farm lobby; the role of labour; Canada’s international standing; and commemoration of the fallen. Canada 1919 exposes the ways in which war shaped and changed Canada – and the ways it did not.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aWorld War, 1914-1918zCanada. 7aHISTORY / Military / Canada.2bisacsh1 aAlexander, Kristine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBercuson, David Jay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBogaert, Kandace, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBowker, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrandon, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCook, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCook, Tim, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDelaney, Douglas E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDurflinger, Serge Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGranatstein, J.L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGranatstein, J.L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHillmer, Norman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHumphries, Mark Osborne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeshen, Jeff, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacDowall, Brian R., econtributo